    "pages.authorityGuidePages.diluteIvPotassiumMaximumConcentration": "Dilute IV potassium: maximum concentration 40 mEq/L for peripheral IV, 80 mEq/L for central line",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.discontinueAllPotassiumSupplementsAnd": "Discontinue tous potassium supplements and potassium-sparing médicaments",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.discontinueMagnesiumcontainingMedications": "Discontinue magnesium-containing médicaments",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.diureticUseLoopthiazideCausesContraction": "Diuretic use (loop/thiazide — causes contraction alkalosis via volume depletion)",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.dka": "DKA:",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.doNotConfuseDilutionalHyponatremia": "Do not confuse dilutional hyponatremia (liquide overload, treat with liquide restriction) with depletional hyponatremia (sodium loss, treat with saline replacement). The traitement is opposite — getting this wrong activé the examen means choosing a harmful intervention.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.doNotSuppressKussmaulRespirations": "Do NOT suppress Kussmaul respirations — they are the corps's compensation mécanisme",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.documentAsCloseToThe": "Document as fermer to the temps of évaluation as possible. Late entries should be clearly identified",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.documentWhatYouSeeHear": "Document what you see, hear, mesurer, and observe — not your interpretation or judgment. Écrire \"patient states 'I feel dizzy'\" rather than \"patient is dizzy\"",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.documentationIsALegalRecord": "Documentation is a legal enregistrer of Soins infirmiers and a competency tested activé les deux the NCLEX and REx-PN. Proper documentation of évaluation findings protects patients, supports continuity of soins, and provides legal defense. Examen questions may ask you to identifier correct documentation practices or recognize documentation erreurs.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.documentationPrinciples": "Documentation Principes",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.drainageAmountcolorTidalingInWater": "Drainage amount/color, tidaling in water seal, subcutaneous emphysema, breath sounds bilateral, tube site integrity",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ecgChanges": "ECG changes:",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ecgChanges2": "ECG changes:",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ecgChangesDysrhythmiasThinkPotassium": "(ECG changes, dysrhythmias) → think potassium or calcium",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.edemaAssessment": "Œdème évaluation:",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.eitherExcessiveLossOfAcid": "Either excessive loss of acid (H⁺) or excessive retention/administration of base (HCO₃⁻).",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.eitherTooMuchAcidProductioningestion": "Either too much acid production/ingestion or too much bicarbonate loss. Use the anion gap to differentiate.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.electrolyteImbalancesRarelyOccurIn": "Électrolyte imbalances rarely occur in isolation. Hypomagnesemia often accompanies hypokalemia. Hypocalcemia frequently coexists with hypomagnesemia. When you see one imbalance activé an examen question, look for autres that commonly co-occur — this modèle recognition is exactly what the NCLEX tests.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.electrolyteQuestionsAppearOnEvery": "Électrolyte questions appear activé every infirmier licensing examen — NCLEX-RN, NCLEX-PN, and REx-PN. They tester your ability to recognize imbalances from clinique données, prioritize infirmier interventions, and understand the physiopathologie behind traitement decisions. The NCSBN tester plan places Électrolytes primarily under Physiological Adaptation and Reduction of Risque Potential, which together compte for 20-32% of the NCLEX-RN examen.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.electrolyteQuestionsOnTheNclex": "Électrolyte questions activé the NCLEX and REx-PN suivre predictable modèles. Knowing these modèles helps you réponse efficiently and accurately, even when the Scénario clinique is unfamiliar.",
