    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ph": "pH:",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ph728Paco55Hco": "pH 7.28, PaCO₂ 55, HCO₃⁻ 24 → Uncompensated respiratoire acidosis (pH faible, CO₂ élevé, HCO₃⁻ normal). Think: COPD exacerbation, opioid overdose, or pneumonia.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ph732Paco30Hco": "pH 7.32, PaCO₂ 30, HCO₃⁻ 15 → Partially compensated metabolic acidosis (pH faible, HCO₃⁻ faible, CO₂ faible from respiratoire compensation). Think: DKA, lactic acidosis, or rénal échec.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ph748Paco28Hco": "pH 7.48, PaCO₂ 28, HCO₃⁻ 24 → Uncompensated respiratoire alkalosis (pH élevé, CO₂ faible, HCO₃⁻ normal). Think: anxiety, douleur, PE, or early septicémie.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.ph750Paco46Hco": "pH 7.50, PaCO₂ 46, HCO₃⁻ 34 → Partially compensated metabolic alkalosis (pH élevé, HCO₃⁻ élevé, CO₂ slightly elevated from respiratoire compensation). Think: vomiting, NG suctioning, or diuretic use.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phIsAbnormalOnlyOne": "pH is anormal, only one valeur (CO₂ or HCO₃⁻) is anormal. The corps has not yet begun to compensate.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phIsDeterminedByThe": "pH is determined by the ratio of HCO₃⁻ to CO₂. Normal ratio is 20:1 (bicarbonate to carbonic acid). Any processus that changes this ratio will alter the pH.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phIsStillAbnormalBut": "pH is still anormal, but les deux CO₂ and HCO₃⁻ are anormal. The corps is trying to compensate but has not fully corrected the pH.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phIsWithinNormalRange": "pH is within Plage normale (7.35-7.45), but les deux CO₂ and HCO₃⁻ are anormal. Look at which end of normal the pH falls to determine the primaire trouble.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phosphatebindingMedicationsCalciumCarbonate": "Phosphate-binding médicaments (calcium carbonate, sevelamer) — administrer WITH meals to bind dietary phosphorus",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.phosphorusHasAnInverseRelationship": "Phosphorus has an inverse relationship with calcium — when one goes up, the autre goes down. This reciprocal relationship is a frequently tested concept. Phosphorus is essentiel for ATP production, bone mineralization, and acid-base buffering.",
    "pages.authorityGuidePages.pneumonia": "Pneumonia:",
